[assistant] 抽取并记录信息: {"user_identity": "", "user_preference": "", "research_direction": "Case management for dementia patients", "filter_requirements": "", "rejection_reasons": "", "other_info": "Systematic review on case management interventions for people with dementia. Background: Over 35 million people living with dementia, high societal costs. Case management is a complex intervention to organize and coordinate care at the individual level as an alternative to early admission to care homes or hospitals. Objectives: To evaluate effectiveness of case management approaches compared to other treatments including 'treatment as usual', standard community treatment, and non-case management interventions from the perspectives of patients, carers, and staff. Search methods: Databases up to 2013 were searched, including ALOIS, Cochrane Dementia group databases, Campbell Collaboration/SORO database. Selection criteria: Randomized controlled trials (RCTs) focused on planning and coordination of care for people with dementia living in the community or their carers. Data collection and analysis: Standard methodological procedures from The Cochrane Collaboration. Two review authors independently extracted data using Cochrane criteria. For continuous outcomes, mean difference (MD) or standardised mean difference (SMD) along with 95% CI. Fixed- or random-effects model applied as appropriate. For binary data, odds ratio (OR) and 95% CI. Heterogeneity assessed by I² statistic. Main results: 13 RCTs involving 9615 participants. Case management group had lower institutionalisation risk; significant reductions in hospital admissions at six months (OR 0.82), but uncertain effects at other time points. Some evidence of benefits in carer burden reduction at six months, though uncertain at later follow-ups. Other outcomes showed mixed results with some improvement in carer well-being and cost reductions. Authors' conclusions: Mixed evidence on case management effectiveness across different time points; heterogeneity between interventions and outcomes; some evidence to reduce care home admissions and costs but uncertain long-term effects."}
